TY  - CPAPER
AU  - Steenhaut, K.
AU  - Degieter, K.
AU  - Dirkx, E.
TI  - Scheduling mechanisms and admission control policies for DQDB
LA  - eng
JF  - 2nd Asia-pacific Conference on Communications
PY  - 1996
PB  - Waseda Univ.
AB  - With the rapid development in multimedia communications, the problem of dealing with traffic with different quality of service (QoS) requirements has become a crucial one. Scheduling of delay sensitive and non delay sensitive traffic must be optimised in order to achieve a maximum utilisation of the medium while guaranteeing the QoS requirements of time constrained services It is not possible to guarantee the demanding and varying QoS of connection oriented (GO) services if all traffic is subjected indiscriminately to contention for the common medium, particularly under heavy load. The use of an access priority mechanism is necessary. The higher priorities should be reserved for connection oriented services with stringent jitter and delay requirements such as voice and video. Connectionless (CL) services for which no quality contract was agreed, are at the lowest priority level. Recently, Budrikis (1993, 1991) proposed to extend the queued arbitrated (QA) access method described in the IEEE 802.6 DQDB MAN standard to allow more than one request in the distributed queue at any time. This facility, operating at a high priority, allows the accommodation of time critical CO services on a shared medium. We study the impact of the burstiness of high priority (HP) traffic on the mean and variance of access delay observed for HP segments, for growing internode distance and increased presence of low priority (LP) traffic. These measurements are performed on a simplified centralised queueing model and on a detailed simulation model for the DQDB and the discrepancies between target and reality are discussed.
ER  -

TY  - CPAPER
AU  - Yuang, M. C.
AU  - Chen, C. S.
TI  - Distributed admission control for supporting isochronous traffic in DQDB MANs
LA  - eng
JF  - Icc '95 Seattle. Communications - Gateway To Globalization. 1995 Ieee International Conference on Communications (cat. No.95ch35749)
VL  - 2
PY  - 1995
SN  - 0780324862, 9780780324862
PB  - IEEE
DO  - 10.1109/ICC.1995.524238
AB  - Distributed queue dual bus (DQDB) metropolitan area networks (MANs) provide data and isochronous services using the connection-less queued arbitrated (QA) and connection-oriented pre-arbitrated (PA) access schemes, respectively. Essentially, the DQDB-PA scheme adopts a connection management procedure which requires laborious exchanges of control messages. Besides, the scheme disregards how bandwidth is allocated for each type of traffic. This paper proposes a distributed admission control (DAC) mechanism for supporting isochronous traffic in DQDB MANs. DAC is composed of two components, the bandwidth allocator and the connection manager. Based on a Markovian model, the bandwidth allocator dynamically allocates appropriate bandwidth to isochronous data according to the current and imminent isochronous traffic load. The bandwidth allocator consequently assures a given quality of service (QOS) requirement of the isochronous traffic with respect to the blocking probability. Moreover, requiring no direct confirmation exchanges, the connection manager allows connections to be admitted and disconnected in an implicit and distributed manner. Finally the paper also presents simulation results which demonstrate the performance superiority of DAC with respect to a set of QOS indexes, such as call admission delay, call blocking probability, and aggregate system throughput.
ER  -

TY  - CPAPER
AU  - Leung, V. C. M.
AU  - Qian, N.
TI  - Call control signaling for personal communications over interconnected metropolitan area networks
LA  - eng
JF  - 1994 Networks for Personal Communications Conference Proceedings (cat. No.94th0653-6)
SP  - 1
EP  - 5
PY  - 1994
SN  - 0780319133, 9780780319134
PB  - IEEE
DO  - 10.1109/NPC.1994.337949
AB  - A distributed personal communication network (PCN) architecture employing interconnected IEEE 802.6 metropolitan area networks (MAN's) has been proposed as a means of handling the anticipated heavy traffic and call processing load of future PCN's employing microcellular wireless access. It employs pre-arbitrated (PA) isochronous access with silence detection for voice transport, and high priority queue-arbitrated (QA) packet access for signaling. Efficient and reliable signaling procedures are required for call control. Particularly for call setups and handoffs. These procedures are presented and analyzed in this paper, along with the supporting system architecture. Simulation results show that the network capacity is constrained by the call setup delay performance. Alternative signaling system architectures, involving different placements of call control network elements, are evaluated. The overlap inter-MAN call setup procedure is proposed to reduce delays. Different call handoff procedures are formulated according to the type of handoff and the resulting change in call connectivity. Most handoffs are intra-MAN, requiring simple procedures with short delays.
ER  -

